[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] The **builder pattern** is a design pattern that provides a flexible solution to various object creation problems in object-oriented programming.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] The builder pattern separates the construction of a complex object from its representation.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] It is one of the 23 classic design patterns described in the book *Design Patterns* and is sub-categorized as a creational pattern.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] Creating and assembling the parts of a complex object directly within a class is inflexible.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] It commits the class to creating a particular representation of the complex object and makes it impossible to change the representation later independently from (without having to change) the class.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] A class (the same construction process) can delegate to different `Builder` objects to create different representations of a complex object.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] The intent of the builder design pattern is to separate the construction of a complex object from its representation.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] By doing so, the same construction process can create different representations.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Director` class doesn't create and assemble the `ProductA1` and `ProductB1` objects directly.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] Instead, the `Director` refers to the `Builder` interface for building (creating and assembling) the parts of a complex object, which makes the `Director` independent of which concrete classes are instantiated (which representation is created).
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] The `Builder1` class implements the `Builder` interface by creating and assembling the `ProductA1` and `ProductB1` objects.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Director` object calls `buildPartA()` on the `Builder1` object, which creates and assembles the `ProductA1` object.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] Thereafter, the `Director` calls `buildPartB()` on `Builder1`, which creates and assembles the `ProductB1` object.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] Abstract interface for creating objects (product).
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] Constructs and assembles parts to build the objects.
[src:factory-boy/builder-pattern] The Director assembles a bicycle instance in the example above, delegating the construction to a separate builder object that has been given to the Director by the Client.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **factory method pattern** is a design pattern that uses factory methods to deal with the problem of creating objects without having to specify their exact classes.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Rather than by calling a constructor, this is accomplished by invoking a factory method to create an object.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Factory methods can be specified in an interface and implemented by subclasses or implemented in a base class and optionally overridden by subclasses.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] It is one of the 23 classic design patterns described in the book *Design Patterns* and is subcategorized as a creational pattern.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] This enables the creation of subclasses that can change the way in which an object is created (for example, by redefining which class to instantiate).
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] According to *Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software*: "Define an interface for creating an object, but let subclasses decide which class to instantiate.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Creating an object often requires complex processes not appropriate to include within a composing object.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The object's creation may lead to a significant duplication of code, may require information inaccessible to the composing object, may not provide a sufficient level of abstraction or may otherwise not be included in the composing object's concerns.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The factory method design pattern handles these problems by defining a separate method for creating the objects, which subclasses can then override to specify the derived type of product that will be created.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The factory method pattern relies on inheritance, as object creation is delegated to subclasses that implement the factory method to create objects.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The pattern can also rely on the implementation of an interface.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Creator` class that requires a `Product` object does not instantiate the `Product1` class directly.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Instead, the `Creator` refers to a separate `factoryMethod()` to create a product object, which makes the `Creator` independent of the exact concrete class that is instantiated.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Subclasses of `Creator` can redefine which class to instantiate.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] In this example, the `Creator1` subclass implements the abstract `factoryMethod()` by instantiating the `Product1` class.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] A maze game may be played in two modes, one with regular rooms that are only connected with adjacent rooms, and one with magic rooms that allow players to be transported at random.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] `Room` is the base class for a final product (`MagicRoom` or `OrdinaryRoom`).
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] `MazeGame` declares the abstract factory method to produce such a base product.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] `MagicRoom` and `OrdinaryRoom` are subclasses of the base product implementing the final product.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] `MagicMazeGame` and `OrdinaryMazeGame` are subclasses of `MazeGame` implementing the factory method producing the final products.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Factory methods thus decouple callers (`MazeGame`) from the implementation of the concrete classes.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] This makes the `new` operator redundant, allows adherence to the open–closed principle and makes the final product more flexible in the event of change.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] This C++23 implementation is based on the pre C++98 implementation in the *Design Patterns* book.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The above code depicts the creation of an interface called `IPerson` and two implementations called `Villager` and `CityPerson`.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Based on the type passed to the `PersonFactory` object, the original concrete object is returned as the interface `IPerson`.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] A factory method is just an addition to the `PersonFactory` class.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] It creates the object of the class through interfaces but also allows the subclass to decide which class is instantiated.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] In this example, `MakeProduct` is used in `concreteFactory`.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] As a result, `MakeProduct()` may be invoked in order to retrieve it from the `IProduct`.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] Custom logic could run after the object is obtained in the concrete factory method.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] `GetObject` is made abstract in the factory interface.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The `MazeGame` uses `Room` but delegates the responsibility of creating `Room` objects to its subclasses that create the concrete classes.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The `MazeGame` constructor is a template method that adds some common logic.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] It refers to the `makeRoom()` factory method that encapsulates the creation of rooms such that other rooms can be used in a subclass.
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] This PHP example shows interface implementations instead of subclassing (however, the same can be achieved through subclassing).
[src:factory-boy/factory-method-pattern] The factory method can also be defined as `public`and called directly by the client code (in contrast to the previous Java example).
