[src:factory-boy/introduction] The purpose of factory_boy is to provide a default way of getting a new instance, while still being able to override some fields on a per-call basis.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] This section will drive you through an overview of factory_boy’s feature.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] New users are advised to spend a few minutes browsing through this list of useful helpers.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] Users looking for quick helpers may take a look at Common recipes, while those needing detailed documentation will be interested in the Reference section.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] When a field has a unique key, each object generated by the factory should have a different value for that field.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] To set or reset the sequence counter see Forcing a sequence counter.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] In simple cases, calling a function is enough to compute the value.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] For complex cases when you happen to write a specific function, the `@factory.lazy_attribute` decorator should be more appropriate.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] Some fields may be deduced from others, for instance the email based on the username.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] Once a “base” factory has been defined for a given class, alternate versions can be easily defined through subclassing.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] Some classes take a few, non-kwarg arguments first.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] Some classes are better described with a few, simple parameters, that aren’t fields on the actual model.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] For 1.X versions, the `create` will actually call `AssociatedClass.objects.create`, as for a Django model.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] Starting from 2.0, `factory.Factory.create()` simply calls `AssociatedClass(**kwargs)`.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] You should use `DjangoModelFactory` for Django models.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] When a `Factory` includes related fields (`SubFactory`, `RelatedFactory`), the parent’s strategy will be pushed onto related factories.
[src:factory-boy/introduction] The default strategy can be changed by setting the `class Meta` `strategy` attribute.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:factory-boy/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:factory-boy/orms] factory_boy provides custom `Factory` subclasses for various ORMs, adding dedicated features.
[src:factory-boy/orms] The first versions of factory_boy were designed specifically for Django, but the library has now evolved to be framework-independent.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Most features should thus feel quite familiar to Django users.
[src:factory-boy/orms] All factories for a Django `Model` should use the `DjangoModelFactory` base class.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Dedicated class for Django `Model` factories.
[src:factory-boy/orms] All queries to the related model will be routed to the given database.
[src:factory-boy/orms] When `django_get_or_create` is used, be aware that any new values passed to the Factory are **not** used to update an existing model.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Transitional option to prevent `DjangoModelFactory`’s `_after_postgeneration` from issuing a duplicate call to `save()` on the created instance when `factory.PostGeneration` hooks return a value.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Applies `make_password()` to the clear-text argument before to generate the object.
[src:factory-boy/orms] When the `password` argument is `None`, the resulting password is unusable as if `set_unusable_password()` were used.
[src:factory-boy/orms] This is distinct from setting the password to an empty string.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Just as Django’s `django.db.models.ImageField` requires the Python Imaging Library, this `ImageField` requires it too.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Signals are often used to plug some custom code into external components code; for instance to create `Profile` objects on-the-fly when a new `User` object is saved.
[src:factory-boy/orms] This may interfere with finely tuned `factories`, which would create both using `RelatedFactory`.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Disable the list of selected signals when calling the factory, and reactivate them upon leaving.
[src:factory-boy/orms] factory_boy supports Mogo-style models, through the `MogoFactory` class.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Mogo is a wrapper around the `pymongo` library for MongoDB.
[src:factory-boy/orms] factory_boy supports MongoEngine-style models, through the `MongoEngineFactory` class.
[src:factory-boy/orms] mongoengine is a wrapper around the `pymongo` library for MongoDB.
[src:factory-boy/orms] If the `associated class` is a `mongoengine.EmbeddedDocument`, the `MongoEngineFactory`’s `create` function won’t “save” it, since this wouldn’t make sense.
[src:factory-boy/orms] This feature makes it possible to use `SubFactory` to create embedded document.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Factory_boy also supports SQLAlchemy models through the `SQLAlchemyModelFactory` class.
[src:factory-boy/orms] To work, this class needs an SQLAlchemy session object affected to the `Meta.sqlalchemy_session` attribute.
[src:factory-boy/orms] SQLAlchemy session to use to communicate with the database when creating an object through this `SQLAlchemyModelFactory`.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Control the action taken by `sqlalchemy_session` at the end of a create call.
[src:factory-boy/orms] When `sqlalchemy_get_or_create` is used, be aware that any new values passed to the Factory are **not** used to update an existing model.
[src:factory-boy/orms] Since SQLAlchemy is a general purpose library, there is no “global” session management system.
[src:factory-boy/orms] See the excellent SQLAlchemy guide on scoped_session for details of `scoped_session`’s usage.
[src:factory-boy/orms] The basic idea is that declarative parts of the code (including factories) need a simple way to access the “current session”, but that session will only be created and configured at a later point.
[src:factory-boy/orms] The `scoped_session` handles this, by virtue of only creating the session when a query is sent to the database.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Changes that may require regression testing include bug fixes, software enhancements, configuration changes, and even substitution of electronic components (hardware).
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] As regression test suites tend to grow with each found defect, test automation is frequently involved.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Sometimes a change impact analysis is performed to determine an appropriate subset of tests (*non-regression analysis*).
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] As software is updated or changed, or reused on a modified target, emergence of new faults and/or re-emergence of old faults is quite common.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Sometimes re-emergence occurs because a fix gets lost through poor revision control practices (or simple human error in revision control).
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Often, a fix for a problem will be "fragile" in that it fixes the problem in the narrow case where it was first observed but not in more general cases which may arise over the lifetime of the software.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Frequently, a fix for a problem in one area inadvertently causes a software bug in another area.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] It may happen that when a feature is redesigned some of the same mistakes that were made in the original implementation of the feature also occur in the redesign.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] In most software development situations, it is considered good coding practice, when a bug is located and fixed, to record a test that exposes the bug and re-run that test regularly after subsequent changes to the program.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Although this may be done through manual testing procedures using programming techniques, it is often done using automated testing tools.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Common strategies are to run such a system after every successful compile (for small projects), every night, or once a week.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Those strategies can be automated by an external tool.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Regression testing is an integral part of the extreme programming software development method.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] In this method, design documents are replaced by extensive, repeatable, and automated testing of the entire software package throughout each stage of the software development process.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Regression testing is done after functional testing has concluded, to verify that the other functionalities are working.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] In the corporate world, regression testing has traditionally been performed by a software quality assurance team after the development team has completed work.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] However, defects found at this stage are the most costly to fix.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] This problem is being addressed by the rise of unit testing.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Although developers have always written test cases as part of the development cycle, these test cases have generally been either functional tests or unit tests that verify only intended outcomes.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Developer testing compels a developer to focus on unit testing and to include both positive and negative test cases.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] This technique checks all the test cases on the current program to check its integrity.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Though it is expensive as it needs to re-run all the test cases, it ensures that there are no errors because of the modified code.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Unlike Retest all, this technique runs a part of the test suite (owing to the cost of retest all) if the cost of selecting the part of the test suite is less than the Retest all technique.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Prioritize the test cases so as to increase a test suite's rate of fault detection.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Test case prioritization techniques schedule test cases so that the test cases that are higher in priority are executed before the test cases that have a lower priority.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] This technique is a hybrid of regression test selection and test case prioritization.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Regression testing is performed when changes are made to the existing functionality of the software or if there is a bug fix in the software.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Regression testing can be achieved through multiple approaches; if a *test all* approach is followed, it provides certainty that the changes made to the software have not affected the existing functionalities, which are unaltered.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] In agile software development—where the software development life cycles are very short, resources are scarce, and changes to the software are very frequent—regression testing might introduce a lot of unnecessary overhead.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Regression testing can be used not only for testing the *correctness* of a program but often also for tracking the quality of its output.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] For instance, in the design of a compiler, regression testing could track the code size and the time it takes to compile and execute the test suite cases.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] — Fred Brooks, *The Mythical Man Month*, p.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Regression tests can be done at any level, from unit through to system integration.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Functional tests exercise the complete program with various inputs.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] These tests are often automated due to the need for repetition, and may be done by test tools that are not part of the compiler suite.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Non-functional tests assess aspects such as performance, security, or reliability.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] Conducting non-functional regression tests presents additional challenges.
[src:factory-boy/regression-testing] For example, detecting changes in performance is often statistically complex, while security issues typically arise from vulnerabilities in the software ecosystem rather than from individual code changes.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] A **test fixture** is a device used to consistently test some item, device, or piece of software.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Test fixtures are used in the testing of electronics, software and physical devices.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In testing electronic equipment such as circuit boards, electronic components, and chips, a test fixture is a device or setup designed to hold the device under test in place and allow it to be tested by being subjected to controlled electronic test signals.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Examples are a bed of nails tester or smart fixture.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Test fixtures can come in different shapes, sizes, and functions.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] There are several different types of test fixtures, including In-Circuit Test Fixtures, Functional Test Fixtures, and Wireless Test Fixtures.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In Circuit Test (ICT) fixtures individually test each component on a PCB, while functional test fixtures assess the entire board's functionality.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Functional test fixtures simulate real-world conditions, whereas ICT is more focused on detecting assembly defects like short circuits or missing components.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] An In-Circuit Test fixture can come in both Inline and Standard variations.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] An Inline Test Fixture is designed for fast, automated testing directly within a production line, ideal for high-volume manufacturing where continuous testing maximises efficiency.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] A Standard Test Fixture, on the other hand, usually requires manual loading, making it well-suited to smaller-scale or specialised testing.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In the context of software, a test fixture (also called "test context") is used to set up the system state and input data needed for test execution.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] For example, the Ruby on Rails web framework uses YAML to initialize a database with known parameters before running a test.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] This allows for tests to be repeatable, which is one of the key features of an effective test framework.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In most cases, a custom test fixture will normally require custom test software.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] This software is created in order to ensure optimal testing performance and seamless integration.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] The custom software can be configured to carry out a number of different tests from BIST (Built-In Self Test) to advanced JTAG Implementation.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Test fixtures can be set up three different ways: in-line, delegate, and implicit.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Delegate setup places the test fixture in a separate standalone helper method that is accessed by multiple test methods.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Implicit setup places the test fixture in a setup method which is used to set up multiple test methods.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] This differs from delegate setup in that the overall setup of multiple tests is in a single setup method where the test fixture gets created rather than each test method having its own setup procedures and linking to an external test fixture.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] The main advantage of a test fixture is that it allows for tests to be repeatable since each test is always starting with the same setup.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Test fixtures also ease test code design by allowing the developer to separate methods into different functions and reuse each function for other tests.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Further, test fixtures preconfigure tests into a known initial state instead of working with whatever was left from a previous test run.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] A disadvantage is that it could lead to duplication of test fixtures if using in-line setup.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] It is considered bad practice when implicit test fixtures are too general, or when a test method sets up a test fixture and does not use it during the test.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] A more subtle issue is if the test methods ignore certain fields within the test fixture.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Another bad practice is a test setup that contains more steps than needed for the test; this is a problem seen in in-line setup.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] A test case is considered "unsafe" when it modifies its fixture(s).
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] An unsafe test case can render subsequent tests useless by leaving the fixture in an unexpected state.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] It also causes the order of tests to be important: a modified fixture must be reset if more tests are to be run after an unsafe test.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Examples of fixtures include loading a database with a specific known set of data, erasing a hard disk and installing a known clean operating system installation, copying a specific known set of files, or the preparation of input data as well as set-up and creation of mock objects.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Software which is used to run reproducible tests systematically on a piece of software under test is known as a test harness; part of its job is to set up suitable test fixtures.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In generic xUnit, a *test fixture* is all the things that must be in place in order to run a test and expect a particular outcome.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Frequently fixtures are created by handling *setUp()* and *tearDown()* events of the unit testing framework.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In *setUp()* one would create the expected state for the test and in *tearDown()* it would clean up what had been set up.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] In physical testing, a fixture is a device or apparatus to hold or support the test specimen during the test.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] The influence of test fixtures on test results is important and is an ongoing subject of research.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Many test methods detail the requirements of test fixtures in the text of the document.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Some fixtures employ clamps, wedge grips and pincer grips.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Further types of construction include eccentric roller fixtures, thread grips and button head grips and rope grips.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Mechanical holding apparatuses provide the clamping force via arms, wedges or eccentric wheel to the jaws.
[src:factory-boy/test-fixture] Additionally there are pneumatic and hydraulic fixtures for tensile testing that allow very fast clamping procedures and very high clamping forces.
